%N A387549 Numbers k such that k^2 + 23 is twice a square.
%C A387549 a(n) is the second number B of two numbers (A, B), such that the difference 2*A^2 - B^2 = 23. 2*A156066(n) gives the A value.
%C A387549 a(n) gives the x value solving the Diophantine equation x^2 + 23 = 2*y^2 or the Pell equation x^2 - 2*y^2 = -23. 2*A156066(n) gives the y value.
%D A387549 L. E. Dickson, History of the Theory of Numbers, Vol. II, Diophantine Analysis. AMS Chelsea Publishing, Providence, Rhode Island, 1999, pp. 341-400.
%H A387549 Vladimir Pletser, <a href="/A387549/b387549.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%H A387549 <a href="/index/Rec#order_04">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (0,6,0,-1).
%F A387549 a(n) = a(n-1) + 4*A156066(n-1) + (-1)^(n-1)*(A048655(n-2) + A048655(n-3)) for n > 1 and with A048655(-1) = 3.
%F A387549 a(n) = 6*a(n - 2) - a(n - 4) with a(1) = 3, a(2) = 7, a(3) = 25, a(4) = 45.
%F A387549 a(n)*a(n+3)-a(n+1)*a(n+2) = -2*(34+14*(-1)^n).
%F A387549 a(n) = 2*A154138(n) + 1.
%e A387549 a(1) = 3 because 3^2 + 23 = 32 = 2*4^2.
